title.narrative: OUTPUT 1.3 MATERNAL & ADOLESCENT NUTRITION

description.narrative: Output 3 (Maternal and adolescent nutrition): Government and partners at national and sub-national level have the capacity to scale up evidence-based actions to prevent maternal malnutrition and enhance the delivery of and increase demand for gender responsive evidence-based programmes to improve nutrition for school-age children and adolescents, which contributes to Health And Development In Early Childhood And Adolescence, Immunization Services As Part Of Primary Health Care, Mental Health And Psychosocial Well-Being, Nutrition In Early Childhood, Nutrition Of Adolescents And Women. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Public Engagement, Evaluations, Research And Data, Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Operational Support To Programme Delivery, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: Pregnant and lactating mothers, children aged under 5 years, and adolescents, including the most vulnerable groups utilize quality and equitable essential nutrition services and adopt appropriate diet and care practices

description.narrative: After the breakthrough policy decision to scale up adolescent nutrition interventions nationwide, in 2021 UNICEF made a strenuous effort to strengthen the National School Health Programme as the platform to deliver evidence-based nutrition services for adolescents. This includes strengthening the capacity of programme managers and service providers to deliver adolescent-friendly nutrition interventions across all 34;provinces. In collaboration with the Ministry of Education, Culture, Research and Technology, Indonesian Nutrition Association and UN World Food Programme, UNICEF digitalize nutrition education materials for primary school children. Significant efforts were made to generate quality local evidence on maternal nutrition policy and programmes. | Status:Met | As-of Date:26/11/2021
